Great suggestion — that keeps the designer’s life easy and preserves the gentle, professional look.  
Here’s a compact LaTeX snippet that defines the palette and typography you just described; you can drop it near the top of your Pandoc template (before `\begin{document}`).

```latex
% === Color & Font setup ===
\usepackage{xcolor}
% Define calm palette
\definecolor{PrimaryAccent}{HTML}{577590}
\definecolor{SecondaryAccent}{HTML}{43AA8B}
\definecolor{ReferralHighlight}{HTML}{F3722C}
\definecolor{BodyText}{HTML}{222222}

% Apply body text color and basic font
\color{BodyText}
\usepackage{lato}    % or substitue helvet if Lato unavailable
\renewcommand{\familydefault}{\sfdefault}
\linespread{1.15}

% === Section and divider styling ===
\usepackage{sectsty}
\sectionfont{\color{PrimaryAccent}\bfseries\Large}
\subsectionfont{\color{SecondaryAccent}\bfseries\normalsize}

% Accent rule for dividers
\newcommand{\accentrule}{\noindent\color{SecondaryAccent}\rule{\textwidth}{0.6pt}\par\vspace{6pt}}

% === Call‑out box for warnings/referrals ===
\usepackage[most]{tcolorbox}
\tcbset{
  highlightbox/.style={
    colback=white,
    colframe=ReferralHighlight,
    boxrule=0.8pt,
    arc=3pt,
    left=6pt,right=6pt,top=4pt,bottom=4pt,
  }
}

% Example usage:
% \begin{tcolorbox}[highlightbox]
% \textbf{If distress persists}, encourage contact with a licensed clinician or local crisis line.
% \end{tcolorbox}
```

**How to use**
- Keep the color definitions at the top of your .tex template; they’ll cascade through headings and boxes.  
- `sectsty` handles headline colors, `tcolorbox` creates neat call‑outs, and overall sans‑serif font keeps readability high.  
- Adjust `arc` or `boxrule` in `\tcbset` if you’d like softer or sharper corners.  

